urbed through the rise of western-style nation states and civil societies. Global history allows us to reframe and challenge traditional models for the history of violence and to rethink categories and units of analysis through comparisons. By decentring Europe and exploring alternative patterns of violence, the contributors to this volume articulate the significance of violence in narratives of state- and empire-building, as well as in their failure and decline, while also providing new means of tracing the transition from the early modern to modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aTechnology. 7aHISTORY / Historiography.2bisacsh  aBanditry.  aEarly Modern World.  aIdeology.  aMilitarisation.  aPiracy.  aRaiding.  aRestraint.  aSlavery.  aViolence.  aWar.1 aBurnard, Trevor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharney, Michael W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharters, Erica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharters, Erica, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aClarke, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClulow, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHang, Xing, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoullemare, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoullemare, Marie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLee, Wayne E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiêm, Vũ Đức, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcFarlan